<DocsLayout title="Output Compression" description="How ostk compresses tool output to save tokens. Three-tier pipeline: VTE strip, implicit dedup, semantic dedup. Grammar-aware classification. Dangerous command detection.">
  <p>The kernel compresses every tool output before it enters agent context. Three tiers: strip noise, deduplicate, classify. Agents never see raw terminal output.</p>

  <h2>Three-tier pipeline</h2>
  <p>Every tool result passes through these tiers in order. Each tier is independent — if the embeddings model is missing, only tier 3 is skipped.</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Tier</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>VTE strip</strong></td>
        <td>ANSI escape codes, cursor movement, terminal control sequences. All removed. Zero exceptions. The agent never pays tokens for color codes or progress bar redraws.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Implicit dedup</strong></td>
        <td>Consecutive similar lines collapsed. Levenshtein similarity at 0.3 threshold. Template tokenization normalizes versions, hashes, and paths before comparison &mdash; so <code>v1.2.3</code> and <code>v1.2.4</code> match, and 50 lines of <code>Compiling foo v0.1.x</code> become one line with a count.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Semantic dedup</strong></td>
        <td>Optional third tier. Lines are batch-embedded, classified by signal type (hazard, warning, outcome, progress), and clustered with per-signal thresholds. Hazards cluster at 0.98 (nearly exact &mdash; errors are sacred). Progress clusters at 0.85 (aggressive &mdash; download bars are noise). Requires the embeddings model.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p><strong>In practice:</strong> roughly 80% token savings on tool output. A 10,000-token raw <code>cargo build</code> becomes ~2,000 tokens. The agent gets the same information without the noise.</p>

  <h2>Grammar-aware compression</h2>
  <p>When the kernel recognizes the command (<code>cargo build</code>, <code>npm install</code>, <code>git log</code>), it switches from bulk compression to line-level classification. Every line is tagged:</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Classification</th><th>Behavior</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Hazard</strong></td>
        <td>Always kept. Errors are never compressed away.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Outcome</strong></td>
        <td>Always kept. The agent must see whether the command succeeded.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Noise(Strip)</strong></td>
        <td>Dropped entirely. Build progress, download bars, timing lines.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Noise(Dedup) / Unknown</strong></td>
        <td>Fed through the dedup engine. Similar lines collapse; unique lines survive.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Grammar detection strips environment prefixes and resolves compound command chains. <code>ENV_VAR=x cargo build</code> and <code>cd dir && cargo build</code> both resolve to <code>cargo build</code>.</p>

  <h2>Command categories</h2>
  <p>Before compression runs, the router classifies the command. First match wins.</p>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Category</th><th>Behavior</th><th>Examples</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Dangerous</strong></td>
        <td>Flagged. Output preserved in full with a warning. The agent is told the command is destructive.</td>
        <td><code>rm -rf</code>, <code>git push --force</code>, <code>mkfs</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Narrate</strong></td>
        <td>Silent commands get a human-readable execution summary instead of empty output.</td>
        <td><code>cp</code>, <code>mv</code>, <code>mkdir</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Passthrough</strong></td>
        <td>Output returned verbatim with a metadata footer. For commands whose output IS the answer.</td>
        <td><code>ls</code>, <code>cat</code>, <code>grep</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Structured</strong></td>
        <td>Machine-readable output parsed and reformatted for the agent.</td>
        <td><code>git status</code>, <code>docker ps</code></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td><strong>Condense</strong></td>
        <td>Everything else. Full three-tier pipeline applied.</td>
        <td><code>cargo build</code>, <code>npm install</code></td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  <p>Resolution order: dangerous pattern check first (full command string). Then multi-token subcommand classification. Then single-token. Then Condense as fallback.</p>

  <h2>Dangerous command detection</h2>
  <p>The kernel scans every shell command for destructive patterns before the agent sees the output. Two groups:</p>
  <p><strong>Legacy patterns</strong> &mdash; <code>rm -rf</code>, <code>git push --force</code>, <code>dd</code> to disk, <code>chmod 777</code>, <code>mkfs</code>.</p>
  <p><strong>Threat-modeled patterns</strong> &mdash; pager shell escapes (<code>less</code>, <code>man</code>, <code>vi</code> with <code>!cmd</code>), <code>find</code> with <code>-delete</code>/<code>-exec</code>, <code>awk system()</code>, read tools with write flags (<code>sort -o</code>, <code>uniq -o</code>), network pipe execution (<code>curl|sh</code>, <code>wget|bash</code>), writes to sensitive paths (<code>.ssh</code>, <code>.bashrc</code>, <code>cron</code>), reads of secret paths (<code>/etc/shadow</code>, SSH keys), kernel operations (<code>insmod</code>, <code>sysctl -w</code>, <code>iptables</code>), and wrapper programs that preserve execution (<code>sudo</code>, <code>doas</code>, <code>pkexec</code>, <code>setsid</code>).</p>
  <p>The scan is compound-aware. <code>cd /tmp && rm -rf /</code> triggers. Environment prefixes are stripped. Bias: false positives preferred over missed destructive commands.</p>

  <h2>Embeddings model</h2>
  <p>The semantic dedup tier requires a local embeddings model. Download it:</p>
  <pre><code>ostk embeddings download</code></pre>
  <p>This fetches <strong>potion-base-8M</strong> from HuggingFace (~30 MB). The kernel uses it automatically once available. Without it, the kernel falls back to implicit dedup. No configuration needed either way.</p>

  <h2>What the operator sees</h2>
  <p>Compression is invisible during normal operation. The agent's context contains compressed output. The operator sees compression stats in <code>ostk os metrics</code>:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Total tokens saved this session</li>
    <li>Compression ratio per tool call</li>
    <li>Whether semantic compression is active</li>
  </ul>
  <p>There is nothing to configure. The kernel compresses all tool output by default. You cannot disable it &mdash; there is no reason to feed noise to agents.</p>

